  "prompt": "Why astronauts have a white and an orange-coloured space suit?",
  "response": "Astronauts use different colored space suits for different purposes, primarily for functionality and safety during various phases of their missions.\n\n1. **White Space Suits**:\n   - **Function**: These are typically used for Extravehicular Activities (EVAs), commonly known as spacewalks.\n   - **Reason for Color**: White is chosen primarily for its thermal properties and visibility. It reflects the sun\u2019s rays, helping to regulate the astronaut\u2019s temperature by keeping them cooler in the harsh sunlight of space. It also provides high visibility against the dark backdrop of space.\n\n2. **Orange Space Suits**:\n   - **Function**: These suits are generally worn during launch and re-entry phases.\n   - **Reason for Color**: The orange is specifically chosen for its high visibility. In the event of a landing emergency or sea recovery, the bright orange is easier to spot in the ocean or against the landscape, assisting rescue teams in locating the crew quickly.\n\nThese design considerations ensure that astronauts remain safe and functional during their missions, whether they are outside their spacecraft conducting repairs or during critical phases of travel to and from space.",
